{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=United States v. Moore |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=September 10, |ArgueYear=1971 |DecideDate=May 14, |DecideYear=1973 |FullName=United States of America v. Raymond Moore |Citations=486 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/486/1139/287860/ 1139] |Prior= |Subsequent=[[Certiorari]] denied, 94 S. Ct. 298 (1973). |Holding= |Judges=[[David L. Bazelon]], [[J. Skelly Wright]], [[Carl E. McGowan]], [[Edward Allen Tamm]], [[Harold Leventhal]], [[Spottswood William Robinson III]], [[George MacKinnon]], [[Roger Robb]], [[Malcolm Richard Wilkey]] ([[en banc]]) |PerCuriam=yes |Concurrence=Wilkey |JoinConcurrence=MacKinnon, Robb |Concurrence2=Leventhal |JoinConcurrence2=McGowan |Concurrence3=MacKinnon |Concurrence4=Robb |Dissent=Wright |JoinDissent=Bazelon, Tamm, Robinson |LawsApplied= }} '''''United States v. Moore''''', 486 F.2d 1139 (D.C. Cir. 1973),<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States v. Moore |vol=486 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=1139 |pinpoint= |court=[[D.C. Cir.]] |date=1973 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/486/1139/287860/ |accessdate=2018-06-13 |quote=}}</ref> was a case decided by the [[D.C. Circuit]] that refused to recognize a [[common law]] [[affirmative defense]] of addiction in a criminal prosecution for the possession of [[heroin]].<ref>Bonnie, R.J. et al. ''Criminal Law, Second Edition.'' Foundation Press, New York: 2004, p. 587</ref>
==Decision== The defendant Moore was charged with the possession of heroin, and in his defense sought to introduce psychiatric testimony that because of his heroin [[Substance dependence|addiction]] he lacked substantial capacity to conform his behavior to the standards of the criminal law. The court refused to recognize Moore's proposed common law defense of addiction because of difficulties in administration and inconsistency with the [[Model Penal Code]].<ref>Bonnie, p. 590</ref>
A dissenting opinion by [[Judge J. Skelly Wright]] advocated for the recognition of the common law defense.<ref>Bonnie, p. 587</ref>
